   318	### `reference/compose/healthcheck/smoke.sh`
   319	
   320	Bash script, exits 0 on success. Used by the new CI job and runnable
   321	locally for verification. Behavior:
   322	
   323	```bash
   324	#!/usr/bin/env bash
   325	set -euo pipefail
   326	
   327	# Bring the stack up using .env.example as the source of truth.
   328	# (Copy to a temp .env if invoked from CI to avoid mutating the
   329	# checked-in file.)
   330	TMPENV="$(mktemp)"
   331	trap 'rm -f "$TMPENV"; docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" down -v' EXIT
   332	cp .env.example "$TMPENV"
   333	
   334	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" up -d --wait --wait-timeout 120
   335	
   336	# Assert both long-running services are healthy.
   337	# `--wait` already enforces this, but we re-check for clarity in CI logs.
   338	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" ps
   339	
   340	# Assert all three named volumes were created at compose-up time.
   341	# Compose creates every top-level volume even when no service in the
   342	# project mounts it (the blob volume is mounted by services in 10b/10d).
   343	for vol in eden-postgres-data eden-gitea-data eden-blob-data; do
   344	    docker volume inspect "eden-reference_${vol}" >/dev/null
   345	done
   346	
   347	# Assert Postgres is accepting connections (independent of healthcheck).
   348	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" exec -T postgres \
   349	    pg_isready -U eden -d eden
   350	
   351	# Assert Gitea API responds.
   352	GITEA_PORT="$(grep ^GITEA_HOST_PORT "$TMPENV" | cut -d= -f2)"
   353	curl -fsS "http://localhost:${GITEA_PORT}/api/v1/version" | grep -q '"version":'
   354	
   355	echo "PASS"
   356	```
   357	
   358	Notes:
   359	
   360	- The `trap` ensures teardown runs even on assertion failure, so
   361	  CI runs don't leave dangling volumes.
   362	- `--wait --wait-timeout 120` (Compose v2 feature) makes `up`
   363	  block until every service is healthy or 2min elapses, exiting
   364	  non-zero if any service fails. This is the cleanest way to
   365	  encode "everything came up healthy" in a script.
   366	- The blob volume assertion uses `docker volume inspect` rather
   367	  than parsing Compose's project-prefixed volume name by hand —
   368	  a fragile string concat (`eden-reference_eden-blob-data`) is
   369	  what `docker compose config` emits, but resolving it via
   370	  `compose config` is robust to project-name overrides.
   371	
   372	### `.github/workflows/ci.yml` — new `compose-smoke` job
   373	
   374	```yaml
   375	  compose-smoke:
   376	    name: compose-smoke
   377	    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
   378	    steps:
   379	      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
   380	      - name: Verify docker compose is available
   381	        run: docker compose version
   382	      - name: Run compose smoke
   383	        working-directory: reference/compose
   384	        run: bash healthcheck/smoke.sh
   385	```
   386	
   387	GitHub Actions' `ubuntu-latest` runners ship with Docker and the
   388	Compose v2 plugin pre-installed; no extra setup needed.
   389	
   390	We do **not** add `compose-smoke` to branch protection in this PR.
   391	Reasoning: the existing required checks (`docs-lint`,
   392	`schema-validity`, `python-lint`, `python-typecheck`, `python-test`,
   393	`schema-parity`) are sufficient to gate a 10a merge; adding
   394	`compose-smoke` to protection on the *same* PR that introduces it
   395	risks a chicken-and-egg if the job is flaky on first run. Add to
   396	protection in 10b once the job has a few clean runs under its belt.
